Some other researchers [502] developed high-luminescence perovskite quantum dots coated with MIPs for the detection of phoxim pesticides. Keeping in mind the nature of phoxim pesticide, a siloxane functional monomer with multiple functional groups was used to allow different interactions with the analyte. The CsPbBr3 QDs were then integrated with MIPs by slow hydrolysis of organosilicon monomers in situ. The sensor exhibited an excellent response toward phoxim detection with LOD value of 1.45 ng/mL (Fig. 20
                        ). Table 8
                         lists some pesticides detection using MIPs-based sensors.

Zearalenone presence in wheat was analyzed using HPLC-DAD [662]. Magnetic MIPs were synthesized using 2,4,6-trisacrylamido-3,5-triazine as a functional monomer and quercetin as the dummy template due to the high toxicity of zearalenone. MIPs were then used for MSPE-HPLC analysis (Fig. 24
                     ). LOD for zearalenone analysis was 0.55 ng/g and recovery of 92.1–96.0 %. Some researchers [663] studied the chromatographic separation of hemoglobin based on MIPs. The purpose of the study was to develop Hb-MIPs material that can be used in the recognition and purification of hemoglobin. The operation was carried out by Hb-MIPs synthesis using the Pickering emulsion method [664]. MIPs were then packed in the column and the results showed good efficiency with a dynamic binding capacity of 11.9 mg/mL. Another group [665] studied the screening of dicofol in celery using the ionic liquid molecularly imprinted pipette-tip solid-phase extraction coupled with gas chromatography. Ionic liquid MIPs were synthesized using precipitation polymerization using 1-allyl-3-methylimidazolium bromide as an auxiliary solvent and α-chloro-dichlorodiphenyltrichloroethane as the template. The results showed an excellent efficiency for the purification and separation of dicofol with an average recovery range of 86.6–101.9 %. Some scientists [666] studied the extraction of phthalates from food using magnetic dummy MIPs followed by their determination using GC–MS/MS. The results showed promising efficiency of the developed materials toward the removal of 10 PAEs with a recovery range of 73.7–98.1 %. Table 12
                      contains some of the separation applications of MIPs.
